00:09:19,460 --> 00:09:21,860
and they'd be beautiful, but then they'd get soggy.

199
00:09:21,860 --> 00:09:23,340
And then I discovered in the basement

200
00:09:23,340 --> 00:09:26,140
of the music department at Cornell was David Borden,

201
00:09:27,140 --> 00:09:28,260
who you might not have heard of,

202
00:09:28,260 --> 00:09:30,180
but is legendary in electronic music

203
00:09:30,180 --> 00:09:32,380
because he was really the first electronic musician.

204
00:09:32,380 --> 00:09:36,180
So Bob Mogue, who invented Mogue synthesizers

205
00:09:36,180 --> 00:09:39,420
was a physics student at Cornell like me crossing the street

206
00:09:39,420 --> 00:09:41,140
and eventually he was kicked out

207
00:09:41,140 --> 00:09:42,860
and invented electronic music.

208
00:09:42,860 --> 00:09:45,540
David Borden was the first musician

209
00:09:45,540 --> 00:09:47,060
who created electronic music.

210
00:09:47,060 --> 00:09:49,020
So he's legendary for people like Phil Glass

211
00:09:49,020 --> 00:09:50,460
and Steve Reich.

212
00:09:50,580 --> 00:09:52,940
And so that got me thinking about,

213
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:55,620
I would behave as a scientist in the music department,

214
00:09:55,620 --> 00:09:57,900
but not in the physics department,

215
00:09:57,900 --> 00:09:59,260
but not in the music department,

216
00:09:59,260 --> 00:10:00,100
got me thinking about

217
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:03,820
what's the computational capacity of a musical instrument.

218
00:10:03,820 --> 00:10:07,140
And through Marvin, he introduced me to Todd Backover

219
00:10:07,140 --> 00:10:08,860
at the Media Lab,

220
00:10:08,860 --> 00:10:11,660
who was just about to start a project with Yo-Yo Ma

221
00:10:11,660 --> 00:10:15,180
that led to a collaboration to instrument a cello,

